(307, 1, '2012-02-29 00:23:30', '2012-02-28 18:53:30', '<h3>The No bullshit version</h3>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Outlook India wrote a piece on Bismarque Dias, a very worthy and pioneering candidate from Cumbarjua, Goa. In the course of the article which talks about Goa elections, the constituency, the candidate and his team they have a two word mention of his website "Impressive web presence". You can read it <a title="Impressive Web design" href="http://outlookindia.com/printarticle.aspx?280071" target="_blank">here</a>. No great shakes. But thrills us to no end!</p>\r\nAlso read on <a href="https://twitter.com/#!/HeritageJazz/status/170419037069770752" target="_blank">twitter</a>\r\n\r\n<h3>How we could have put it</h3>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><a title="Impressive Webdesign - Says Outlook" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outlook_(magazine)" target="_blank">Outlook</a> is one of the most widely read weekly English magazines in India with a circulation of over 1.5 million. To put it in perspective, roughly the same number of readers subscribe to <a title="Impressive Webdesign - by Outlook" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_New_York_Times" target="_blank">"The New York Times" Sunday Edition.</a>\r\nSo when  they feature one of our work and call it <a title="Impressive Webdesign" href="http://outlookindia.com/printarticle.aspx?280071" target="_blank">"Impressive"</a> we don''t quite know how to react. </p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The site is <a href="http://www.voteforkindness.org/">http://www.voteforkindness.org/.</a> We volunteered our services for this site and turned it around in record time. The site has helped the campaign reach out to voters, media and opinion leaders across state and nation. We look forward to creating more work that can set new benchmarks in online work and create more "Impressive webdesign" across domains and verticals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">At Ajency we don''t <a title="No bullshit webdesign" href="http://www.ajency.in/no-bullshit/" target="_blank">bullshit</a> and do not mislead you with false pretenses.</p>', '"Impressive Webdesign" - says Outlook', 'Outlook Magazine (India''s leading English weekly magazine) describes our work as impressive!', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'impressive-webdesign', '', '\nhttp://www.ajency.in/no-bullshit/', '2014-04-17 14:12:19', '2014-04-17 08:42:19', '', 0, 'http://www.ajency.in/?p=307', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(327, 1, '2012-07-23 19:02:40', '2012-07-23 13:32:40', 'Ever wondered why HR policies and company practices were available for reading only after you have joined the organization? Why should they be printed and signed and never seen again? It never made sense to me. At Ajency we hope to create what some people call as a "<a title="Naked Organization" href="http://www.google.co.in/search?sourceid=chrome&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;q=naked+organization" target="_blank">Naked Organization</a>". Credit for this line of thought goes to my previous employers at <a title="MangoSpring- Social Enterprise and Collaboration" href="http://www.mangoapps.com//" target="_blank">MangoSpring</a> (a startup based out of Seattle and Pune that I learnt everything I know at).\r\n\r\nIn our effort towards a Naked organization we will have all our office documents in public domain. These are living documents and we hope to keep updating them as our team grows and context changes. Feel free to use them or share them with or without attribution. No copyright applies :)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Ajency offer letter</li>\r\n	<li>Ajency ''No Bullshit'' Manifesto</li>\r\n	<li>Ajency office policies</li>\r\n	<li>Ajency facebook &amp; web surfing policy</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nThese documents were written in conjunction with the early employees of Ajency.in (first four employees). The entire team went for an offsite and put their heads together to figure out the kind of team culture we want to have. \r\n\r\nPictures of the offsite where we wrote the first draft of the documents. \r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'The No Bullshit employee policies and company documents', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'startup-employee-policies', '', '', '2014-04-17 14:12:36', '2014-04-17 08:42:36', '', 0, 'http://www.ajency.in/?p=327', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(329, 1, '2012-07-23 20:03:59', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Different teams have different work ethics. It is most often a factor of the team leaders personal preferences. In smaller teams like ours the founders set the organizations work culture through example. While we appreciate the need for each individual to have their own approach to self discipline we are mindful of the need to have some guidelines.\r\n\r\nIf you find any of the guidelines here do not sit well with you bring it up and talk it out. More often than not it is a matter of understanding each other''s position. Do not leave it ambiguous and do not leave it unsaid.\r\n<h5>What matters: Hours at work or output?</h5>\r\nHonestly we have never understood the difference between the two. A work day consists of 8 hours and if you accomplish your tasks in 5 then you are probably not taking on enough or are taking on work that is below your skillset.  So both the time you spend and the output you deliver are important to us.\r\n\r\nThere are no time sheets or attendance rosters. We hope that you will keep tab on your hours and cover up for any lost time due to late starts or mi-week errands.\r\n<h5>Office timings</h5>\r\nAs our offer letter states we are flexible with your work timings. If you like to start your day an hour later than the rest then so be it. How ever we would like you to be consistent with them. Pick a time and stick to it.\r\n<h5>Surfing at work</h5>\r\nThere are no firewalls. There is no one peeping into your machine. If you want to check your personal mail, play a game on miniclip, read some news; feel free to do so. How ever you might find taking a small walk, making yourself a cup of tea or coffee, reading the newspaper, reading an article in the magazine as a better way to relax. Since our entire work day is spent in front of a computer we strongly encourage  you to take your break by doing stuff offline.\r\n\r\nDo suggest any additions to the office that will help you take short breaks between work.\r\n<h5>Facebook/Twitter at work</h5>\r\nChecking facebook multiple times a day has become a compulsion for most of us. More often than not it is open on one of your browser tabs (the one you hurriedly hide when a team member walks up to your desk!). We personally have fixed time slots for facebook and find that it works best in keeping ourselves disciplined. For example 10 minutes in the morning as we start work and then again post lunch and just before logging off for the day works best for us. You are free to have your own Facebook policy.\r\n<h5>Chat at Work</h5>\r\nWe use Google talk for our office communication. This is with your @ajency.in email id. Though Google allows you to add any one with a google account to your chat client we would prefer you to not do so.  Use of messengers of any sort (gmail, facebook included) is frowned upon. We request you to stay signed off all chat messengers while at work. This applies to chat clients on your phone as well. \r\n<h5>Mobile phone at work</h5>\r\nRespect your coworkers and have your phones on silent mode at all times. Do step out for the calls.\r\n<h5>Dress code at work</h5>\r\nWe are confused on this one. Lot of companies that started out with no dress code had to resort to enforcing one. The common complaint seems to be that ''casual'' dress leads to casual work. We are how ever big fans of comfortable dressing. So loafers, shorts or what ever you feel comfortable in.\r\n<h5>Lunch hours</h5>\r\nThere are no fixed lunch hours. Feel free to take one when you feel hungry. Some of us step out for lunch, while others get something from home. The duration of lunch break is directly proportional to your waist size. 5 minutes for anything about 34 waist size and 1 hour for anything below 30! Ok we are kidding but let''s not make lunch breaks into gossip breaks. 30-45 minutes should be plenty.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'No Bullshit startup culture - Workplace basics', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2012-07-23 20:03:59', '2012-07-23 14:33:59', '', 0, 'http://www.ajency.in/?p=329', 0, 'post', '', 0),
